<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">probability theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, the <b>Poiss=
on distribution</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class=3D=
"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span style=3D"bord=
er-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress follows">=CB=
=88</span><span title=3D"'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title=3D"'w' in 'wind'=
">w</span><span title=3D"/=C9=91=CB=90/: 'a' in 'father'">=C9=91=CB=90</spa=
n><span title=3D"'s' in 'sigh'">s</span><span title=3D"/=C9=92/: 'o' in 'bo=
dy'">=C9=92</span><span title=3D"'n' in 'nigh'">n</span></span>/</a></span>=
</span>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_probability=
_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete probability distribu=
tion">discrete probability distribution</a> that expresses the probability =
of a given number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Event_(probab=
ility_theory)" title=3D"Event (probability theory)">events</a> occurring in=
 a fixed interval of time if these events occur with a known constant mean =
rate and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_independence"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical independence">independently</a>=
 of the time since the last event.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Haight1967_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distributio=
n#cite_note-Haight1967-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It can also be used for the number of =
events in other types of intervals than time, and in dimension greater than=
&nbsp;1 (e.g., number of events in a given area or volume).
The Poisson distribution is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/France" title=3D"France">French</a> mathematician <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sim%C3%A9on_Denis_Poisson" title=3D"Sim=C3=A9on Denis=
 Poisson">Sim=C3=A9on Denis Poisson</a>. It plays an important role for <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete-stable_distribution" title=
=3D"Discrete-stable distribution">discrete-stable distributions</a>.
</p><p>Under a Poisson distribution with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expectation</a> of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> events =
in a given interval, the probability of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> events in the same interval is:<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Yates2014_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-Yates2014-2"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 60">:=E2=80=8A60=E2=80=8A</span>=
</sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\frac {\lambda ^{k}e^{-\lambda }}{k!}}.}">
