For instance, consider a call center which receives an average of <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i> =3D 3</span> calls per minute at all times of =
day. If the number of calls received in any two given disjoint time interva=
ls is independent, then the number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">k</span> of calls received during any minute has a Poisso=
n probability distribution. Receiving  <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> =3D=
 1 to 4</span> calls then has a probability of about&nbsp;0.77, while recei=
ving&nbsp;0 or at least&nbsp;5 calls has a probability of about&nbsp;0.23.
</p><p>A classic example used to motivate the Poisson distribution is the n=
umber of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactive_decay" title=
=3D"Radioactive decay">radioactive decay</a> events during a fixed observat=
ion period.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<p>The distribution was first introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sim%C3%A9on_Denis_Poisson" title=3D"Sim=C3=A9on Denis Poisson">Si=
m=C3=A9on Denis Poisson</a> (1781=E2=80=931840) and published together with=
 his probability theory in his work <i>Recherches sur la probabilit=C3=A9 d=
es jugements en mati=C3=A8re criminelle et en mati=C3=A8re civile</i> (1837=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Poisson1837_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-Poisson1837-4"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 205-207">:=E2=80=
=8A205-207=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The work theorized about the number of wro=
ngful convictions in a given country by focusing on certain <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random=
 variables</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N<=
/span> that count, among other things, the number of discrete occurrences (=
sometimes called "events" or "arrivals") that take place during a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time" title=3D"Time">time</a>-interval of=
 given length. The result had already been given in&nbsp;1711 by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_de_Moivre" title=3D"Abraham de Moivr=
e">Abraham de Moivre</a> in <i>De Mensura Sortis seu; de Probabilitate Even=
tuum in Ludis a Casu Fortuito Pendentibus</i> .<sup id=3D"cite_ref-deMoivre=
1711_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pois=
son_distribution#cite_note-deMoivre1711-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 219">:=E2=80=8A219=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-deMoivre1718_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-deMoivre1718-6"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 14-15">:=E2=80=8A14-=
15=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-deMoivre1721_7-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_n=
ote-deMoivre1721-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=
=3D"Page: 193">:=E2=80=8A193=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Johns=
on2005_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
isson_distribution#cite_note-Johnson2005-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referen=
ce nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 157">:=E2=80=8A157=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Th=
is makes it an example of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stigler%=
27s_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stigler's law">Stigler's law</a> an=
d it has prompted some authors to argue that the Poisson distribution shoul=
d bear the name of de Moivre.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stigler1982_9-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#ci=
te_note-Stigler1982-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hald1984_10-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distributio=
n#cite_note-Hald1984-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In&nbsp;1860, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Newcomb=
" title=3D"Simon Newcomb">Simon Newcomb</a> fitted the Poisson distribution=
 to the number of stars found in a unit of space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Newcom=
b1860_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
isson_distribution#cite_note-Newcomb1860-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
A further practical application was made by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ladislaus_Bortkiewicz" title=3D"Ladislaus Bortkiewicz">Ladislaus =
Bortkiewicz</a> in&nbsp;1898. Bortkiewicz showed that the frequency with wh=
ich soldiers in the Prussian army were accidentally killed by horse kicks c=
ould be well modeled by a Poisson distribution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-vonBortk=
iewitsch1898_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-vonBortkiewitsch1898-12"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 23-25">:=E2=80=8A23-25=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup>.
</p>
