_a_sidewalk_in_Reykjav%C3%ADk.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"333" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2472" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"3296"></a><figcaption>Chewing gum on a sidewalk. The number of pieces =
on a single tile is approximately Poisson distributed.</figcaption></figure=
>
<p>The Poisson distribution may be useful to model events such as:
</p>
<ul><li>the number of meteorites greater than one-meter diameter that strik=
e Earth in a year;</li>
<li>the number of laser photons hitting a detector in a particular time int=
erval;</li>
<li>the number of students achieving a low and high mark in an exam; and</l=
i>
<li>locations of defects and dislocations in materials.</li></ul>
<p>Examples of the occurrence of random points in space are: the locations =
of asteroid impacts with earth (2-dimensional), the locations of imperfecti=
ons in a material (3-dimensional), and the locations of trees in a forest (=
2-dimensional).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-:1-15"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Assumptions_and_validity">A=
ssumptions and validity</h3></div>
<p>The Poisson distribution is an appropriate model if the following assump=
tions are true:
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>,=
 a nonnegative integer, is the number of times an event occurs in an interv=
al.</li>
<li>The occurrence of one event <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
dependence_(probability_theory)" title=3D"Independence (probability theory)=
">does not affect the probability</a> of a second event.</li>
<li>The average rate at which events occur is independent of any occurrence=
s.</li>
<li>Two events cannot occur at exactly the same instant.</li></ul>
<p>If these conditions are true, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">k</span> is a Poisson random variable; the distributio=
n of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> is =
a Poisson distribution.
</p><p>The Poisson distribution is also the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Limit_(mathematics)" title=3D"Limit (mathematics)">limit</a> of a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D"B=
inomial distribution">binomial distribution</a>, for which the probability =
of success for each trial is <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-eleme=
