<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_number_theory"=
 title=3D"Probabilistic number theory">probabilistic number theory</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_X._Gallagher" title=3D"Patric=
k X. Gallagher">Gallagher</a> showed in&nbsp;1976 that, if a certain versio=
n of the unproved <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Hardy%E2%=
80%93Littlewood_conjecture" title=3D"Second Hardy=E2=80=93Littlewood conjec=
ture">prime r-tuple conjecture</a> holds,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hardy1923_70-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_dist=
ribution#cite_note-Hardy1923-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  then the counts of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime n=
umbers</a> in short intervals would obey a Poisson distribution.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Gallagher1976_71-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution#cite_note-Gallagher1976-71"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"law_of_rare_events"></span>
</p>
