gma _{k}=3D{\sqrt {\lambda }}.}"></span> These fluctuations are denoted as =
<i>Poisson noise</i> or (particularly in electronics) as <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shot_noise" title=3D"Shot noise">shot noise</a></=
i>.
</p><p>The correlation of the mean and standard deviation in counting indep=
endent discrete occurrences is useful scientifically. By monitoring how the=
 fluctuations vary with the mean signal, one can estimate the contribution =
of a single occurrence, <i>even if that contribution is too small to be det=
ected directly</i>. For example, the charge <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> on an electron can be estimated by corr=
elating the magnitude of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electr=
ic_current" title=3D"Electric current">electric current</a> with its <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shot_noise" title=3D"Shot noise">shot no=
ise</a>. If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</sp=
an> electrons pass a point in a given time <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">t</span> on the average, the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mean</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" title=3D"Electric current">current</a> i=
s <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle I=3D=
eN/t}">
