tle=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2012)">citat=
ion needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>An everyday example is the graininess that appears as photographs ar=
e enlarged; the graininess is due to Poisson fluctuations in the number of =
reduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silver" title=3D"Silver">s=
ilver</a> grains, not to the individual grains themselves. By <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation" title=3D"Correlation">correlating<=
/a> the graininess with the degree of enlargement, one can estimate the con=
tribution of an individual grain (which is otherwise too small to be seen u=
naided).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white=
-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Cita=
tion_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim =
needs references to reliable sources. (February 2024)">citation needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causal_set" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Causal set">causal set</a> theory the discrete elements =
of spacetime follow a Poisson distribution in the volume.
</p><p>The Poisson distribution also appears in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechan=
ics</a>, especially <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_optics=
" title=3D"Quantum optics">quantum optics</a>. Namely, for a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_harmonic_oscillator" title=3D"Quantum ha=
rmonic oscillator">quantum harmonic oscillator</a> system in a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherent_state" title=3D"Coherent state">coher=
ent state</a>, the probability of measuring a particular energy level has a=
 Poisson distribution.
</p>
